# These are the steps I used to generate the QR codes as found in the QR Codes folder.
# You can generate your own, use the URL to get a QR code on your screen when you monitor the device,
# or use the ones in the folder... I think.  I'm really bad at propagating changes throughout my repo (I'm usually so excited I actually got something working, I forget).


# Download the mft-tool, since it's no longer included in the repository
python3 -m pip install esp-matter-mfg-tool

## Create a new directory to store the output, e.g.:
mkdir ~/qr_out
## CD to that directory, e.g.:
cd ~/qr_out

# Command to generate the out files:
# esp-matter-mfg-tool -v 0xFFF1 -p 0x8000 --vendor-name "TestVendor" --product-name "TestProduct" --discriminator <unique_4_digit_#> -passcode <unique_8_digit_#>
# -v and -p should stay as seen above if you're just making at-home, DIY projects,
# otherwise you might run into issues depending what ecosystem you're using (Home Assistant, Apple, Google, etc.)
# At the very least, keep 0xFFF1, but you can change the -p if you want to organize things
# vendor-name and product-name can be whatever
# --discriminator should be unique, but doesn't have to be, between 0~4095.  It is used during pairing only, in case you power on multiple devices, it helps the system know which of the devices you're referring to
# -passcode should be unique, but doesn't have to be.  It is ued to help prevent someone from hijacking the device.
# E.G:
esp-matter-mfg-tool -v 0xFFF1 -p 0x8000 --vendor-name "PPP" --product-name "PPP-Button" --discriminator 3842 --passcode 48331897

# You will now have a new out folder, which consists of a folder name whatever you used for the -v and -p
# You're mainly interested in the folder with the UUID, e.g.:
cd ~/qr_out/out/fff1_8000/e2b52238-784f-4584-be9d-43d9b6a91c3b

# This folder contains both an image of the qr code need for commissioning, and the bin that will get flashed to the device
# If you want, you can go to https://project-chip.github.io/connectedhomeip/qrcode.html to paste in the MT: code that you can view in the CSV.
# It will generate a different QR than this one, but that's just because they used different error correction levels

# Get the fctry offset from your project's partitions.csv, e.g.
nano ~/code/Matter_Notification_Device/light/partitions.csv
# Look for the row staring with "fctry", and the fourth column consisting of a memory address, e.g. 0x3E0000

# Run the following command to write this info to the correct partition
# esptool.py -p <port> -b <baud_rate> write_flash <partition_offset> path/to/bin_file.bin
# * are accepted wildcards
# E.G., if you're still in the directory containing the .bin:
esptool.py -p /dev/ttyACM0 -b 460800 write_flash 0x3E0000 ./*.bin

# Troubleshooting tool:
# esptool.py -p /dev/ttyACM0 -b 460800 read_flash 0x3E0000 0x6000 verify_dump.bin
# hexdump -C verify_dump.bin | head -n 20

